      <hedline>
        <hl1>So Which Is the 'Education Party'?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Jerrold Ross letter comments on August 14 editorial urging New York City Schools Chancellor Harold Levy and New York State Education Comr Richard Mills to settle differences relating to shortage of qualified teachers in city's schools</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Fighting About the Teacher Shortage'' (editorial, Aug. 14):</p>
        <p>The problem of finding enough certified teachers for New York City's schools can be solved if a plan involving private and public schools of education is created.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Fighting About the Teacher Shortage'' (editorial, Aug. 14):</p>
        <p>The problem of finding enough certified teachers for New York City's schools can be solved if a plan involving private and public schools of education is created.</p>
        <p>Such a plan would vest responsibility for identifying and producing teachers jointly between universities and the school districts that surround their campuses. An exciting career path attracting high school students to enter teaching programs and culminating with rigorous traditional and alternative certification programs could then guarantee certified teachers for every school in the city.</p>
        <p>JERROLD ROSS  New York, Aug. 14, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is dean of the School of Education and Human Services, St. John's University.</p>
      </block>
